<h2>Reconstructing Reality</h2>
<h3>How the brain makes sense of it all</h3>
<p><br />Our brains create for us a coherent representation of the everday world by combining inputs from our sense organs. How does the brain solve the so-called "binding problem", managing to correctly put together the right bits of sensory information? Here are some interesting examples to demonstrate that binding is indeed a problem for the brain, but one that it solves very well - well, most of the time anyway.</p>
